  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "broadcast-loop-singleton-indirection",
      "summary": "Broadcast runtime layering is overly indirection-heavy and global-state bound, reducing reuse and creating hard-to-test coupling for loop orchestration.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/broadcast/state.go",
        "goseg/broadcast/loop.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`state.go` keeps a package-level singleton runtime via `defaultBroadcastStateRuntime = NewBroadcastStateRuntime()` and `resolveDefaultBroadcastStateRuntime()`",
        "`loop.go` keeps package globals for control (`loopRunning`, `loopStopChannel`) and starts/stops a shared goroutine state machine from package-scope functions",
        "`newBroadcastLoopRuntime` mostly stores closures that forward to functions in `state.go` (`constructSystemInfoWithRuntime`, `constructPierInfoWithRuntime`, `constructAppsInfoWithRuntime`) with no additional policy in the loop layer"
      ],
      "suggestion": "Replace package-level singleton/control state with an explicit loop coordinator object returned by constructor, so each caller can own an isolated loop runtime and channel set; keep only dependency interfaces needed for actual behavior (e.g., state source and ticker policy) and collapse pure forwarding closures into direct method calls.",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "impact_scope": "subsystem",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "callback-seam-overhead"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "cross-module-callback-granularity",
      "summary": "Multiple subsystems duplicate broad callback-runtime bundles that act as DI boilerplate rather than cohesive abstractions.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/startuporchestrator/startup_orchestrator.go",
        "goseg/importer/importer.go",
        "goseg/shipworkflow/operations_runtime.go",
        "goseg/docker/orchestration/runtime_ops.go",
        "goseg/system/wifi_runtime_api.go",
        "goseg/system/wifi_runtime_methods.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "startuporchestrator defines nested runtime structs and per-feature resolver/validation paths (`startupInitRuntime`, `startBackgroundServicesRuntime`, `validate`, `default...`, `WithDefaults`-style wiring)",
        "importer splits runtime into `importerStorageRuntime`, `importerUploadRuntime`, `importerProvisionRuntime` with `validateImporter*Runtime` guards and per-capability defaults",
        "`shipworkflow` runtime embeds multiple orchestration runtime structs and resolves through `resolveWorkflowRuntime` for most operations",
        "`docker/orchestration/runtime_ops.go` exports many broad runtime structs (`RuntimeContainerOps`, `RuntimeUrbitOps`, `RuntimeStartupOps`, etc.) that mostly mirror existing package functions"
      ],
      "suggestion": "Define smaller, behavior-based seam interfaces at real boundaries (config/io, process lifecycle, transport) and inject concrete adapters per subsystem; eliminate repeated global validation layers by using one composition root per bounded context (startup/importer/workflow) with explicit required capabilities.",
      "confidence": "high",
      "impact_scope": "codebase",
      "fix_scope": "architectural_change",
      "root_cause_cluster": "callback-seam-overhead"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "config-patch-registry-overdesign",
      "summary": "Config patch abstraction is over-generic and repetitive, making intent hard to read and increasing regression risk for each new field.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/config/config_update_registry.go",
        "goseg/structs/configs.go",
        "goseg/config/config.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`config_update_registry.go` introduces several generic helper layers (`confPatchFieldSpec`, `confPatchSectionBuilder`, `confPatchFieldBinding`, `merge*Ref`) plus dozens of thin merge helpers",
        "new field registration in `allConfPatchFields()` is highly repetitive and mixes parse, validation, merge, and assignment concerns in a single chained DSL",
        "several merge rules differ only by selector predicates (`mergeStringSetIfNonEmptyRef`, `stringSetDirectRef`, `intSetIfNonZeroRef`, `mergeSliceWhen`) while the call sites remain verbose",
        "high mention count in wide-params report for config files indicates frequent parameter/context bundling rather than direct struct-driven operations"
      ],
      "suggestion": "Replace the generic builder-heavy DSL with a smaller, explicit registry format (or generated descriptor) where each patch key maps to one parser, one merge strategy, and one apply path; this will lower abstraction depth and centralize error semantics.",
      "confidence": "medium",
      "impact_scope": "module",
      "fix_scope": "multi_file_refactor",
      "root_cause_cluster": "generic-dsl-bloat"
    }
  ],
  "retrospective": {
    "root_causes": [
      "DI/seam scaffolding was applied uniformly as a default pattern, even when wrappers mostly forward calls.",
      "Callback-heavy runtime structs became the unit of abstraction, so cross-cutting concerns are encoded as structural boilerplate instead of intentful interfaces."
